{"/service/ndnp/txdn/batch_txdn_evans_ver01/data/sn86063730/00332894195/1930021702/0305.xml":{"full_text":"tHe Snramsuflle fieralO\nEstablished July 4, 1892\nEntered ss second-class matter In the Postoffice\nBrownsville, rexaa\nTHE BROWNSVILLE HEKALO PUBLISHING\nCOMPANY\nSubscription Bates\u2014Daily and Sunday (7 Issues i\nOne Year .$9.00\nSix Months\nThree Months..\nOne Month. .75\nMEMBER OP THE ASSOCIATED PRESS\nThe Associated Press is exclusively entitled to the use\n(or publication of all news dispatches credited to It or\ntot otherwise credited In this paper, and also the\njocal news published herein.\nHarlingen Office. Reese-WU-Mond Hotel. Phone 1020.\nTEXAS DAILY PRESS LEAGUE\nNational Advertising Representatives\nDallas. Texas. 512 Mercantile Bank Building.\nKansas City. Mo.. 306 Coca Cola Building.\nChicago, III.. Association Building.\nNew York, 350 Madison Avenue.\nSt. Louis. 502 Star Building.\nLos Angeles. Cal., Room 1015 New Orpheum Bldg.,\n846 8. Broadway.\nSan Francisco, Cal.. 318 Kohl Building.\nHome Industries and How They\nAre Protected\nThe slogan of the republican party and the re\npublican administration that high tariffs are neces\nsary for the protection of American manufacturing,\nAmerican money and American labor.\nTexas has a vast army of small investors and wage\nworkers engaged in the petroleum industry. They\nare known as Independents. They compete with for\neign labor. Foreign crude Is on the free list and\nthe senate of Texas. 15 to 7, voted that the Texas\nIndependents in the oil game are not entitled to the\ntariff protection given the makers of things in the\nNorth and the East.\nThat is. the growers and independents producers of\nthings were given a legislative slap on the jaw. There\nare 31 senators. Eight were absent. They failed to\nfigure in the voting as the record for the press was\nmade by the correspondents.\nThere is a way to avoid tackling real economic\nIssues. All a politician or lawmaker has to do is to\nyell from the housetops for law enforcement of the\n18th amendment and the Volstead act. Law en\nforcement Is to be commended, but why make It a\nsmoke screen for the purpose of avoiding the live\neconomic Issues which concern the farmers of Ameri\nca and their rapidly decaying Industry?\nThese Issues cannot be choloroformed. AH the sur\nface signs Indicate growers of things, the producers of\nthe important American staples, are weary of serving\nas hewers of wood and drawers of water for the\nmakers of things and their Grundy and Watsons\nwho shape the legislation of the country.\n0rgani7ed Agriculture Rebels\n\"Organized agriculture is in rebellion against the\npending tariff bill.\u201d reads a Washington dispatch.\nRepresentatives of seven of the leading farm organl\ngatlons of the United States, in an open letter ad\ndressed to members of the senate, asserted \"the pres\nent state of the senate measure would prevent a\nrestoration of a balanced agriculture.\u201d\nThis followed in the wake of the departure of Pres\nHerbert Hoover and General Publicity Agent Mark\nBui 11 van to a point on the Florida coast, \"where the\nfishing Is splendid.\u201d\nWell, what are the members of the seven leading\nfarm organizations of the United States going to do\naboaut It In the elections this year?\nThere are 6,500.000 farmers in the 48 states.\nThey could play the devil in many western and\nnorthwestern states with the official programs and\nthe slate nominees of the G. O. P.\u2014that is, if they\nhad the nerve to strike a blow In defense of their\nown convictions and for the protection of their own\nproduct and firesides.\nWill they? They haven\u2019t to date\u2014since the close\nof the war between the states.\nA Great American Nearing\nThe End\nWilliam Howard Taft Is said to be hanging on the\nbrink of the grave. If so a great and patriotic Ameri\ncan of the old school is about to pass out of the\npicture to the regret of millions.\nREGARDING SKI-JUMPING\n(Copyright, 1930, by The Associated Newspapers.)\nDear Editor: Will you kindly tell me how you rate\nski-jumping among the activities of life? Having\nbeen viewing the news reels and rotogravure sections\nlately, I have been a little surprised to note the vast\nnumber of people engaged in this sport. I am a young\nman, 23 years of age, anxious to get ahead in life, but\nI am meeting with no success. Nobody seems interest\ned in me. No one pays attention Do you think it\nis because I am not a ski-jumper?\n9\nWorried Reader.\n\nDear Worried: Your letter reflects the quandary\nof thousands of newspaper readers and moving pic\nture fans. Your question is timely. We are glad you\nasked. Ski-jumping is (unless the news reel and\nrotogravure editors are fooling us) one of the world\u2019s\nmajor interests. Everybody seems to be doing it, and\nit tends to make a man who never leaped across aa\nicy valley in his life feel awfully inadequate, not to\nsay silly.\n\nIt Is coming more and more to be realized that with\nout ski-jumping ability a youth is under a serious\nhandicap in life, especially from December to Apnl.\nIf he lives in a country where there is any snow it\nis absolutely necessary that he jump. And even if he\nlives in a land where there is no snow or ice he finds\nit essential to grasp the detail of the sport and be\nable to discuss It, since there is a point in all con\nversations at which the subject arises.\n\nA young man who gets about at all with people\nwho read the papers and go to the picture houses\nwill be under a great advantage if he himself is a\nmaster of ski-jumping, and it means a lot to an\nolder man to be able to say \"I am an old ski-jumper\nmyself.\u201d If it is impossible for you to take up ski\njumping buy, beg or borrow a pair of skates at once,\nmy boy, and attain a reasonable skill at it. It will\nhelp you socially and In business.\u201d\n\nBrokerage houses and insurance companies are be\ncoming glutted with football, baseball and golf stars\nbut a good bond salesman who has won fame at\nski-jumping Is hard to find. His services command\na premium.\n\nSki-Jumping is a character-builder. It develops\nnerve, courage, self-confidence, poise and assurance.\nA youth who has become a Grade A ski-jumper never\nagain will know that intuitive fear of falling off a\nroof or being thrown out of college.\n\nBy all means, young man. take up ski-jumpin?\nbefore it is too late. Everybody else has.\nANOTHER NAME FOR THE Hl\u2019DDLE\n\"May I see Mr. Ostcrbaum?\u2019\u2019 asked the caller at\nthe office of one of the city\u2019s big business men.\n\u2022\u2022Sorry.\u201d replied the stenographer who had been\nreading the newspapers, \u201cbut he can't be seen just\nnow. He\u2019s in plenary session.\u201d\nUNION, N. J., Feb. 6.\u2014(A1)\u2014Miss Irene Franklin,\nactress, who planned last fall to establish a vacation\nhome for poor chorus girls here, has changed her\nmind and bought a yacht.\n\nThat for charity; And that and that!\n\nA census shows there are twelve Henry Fords in\nthe city of Detroit. Chicago isn\u2019t getting such a bad\nbreak after all.\nA tabloid editor\u2019s idea of complete frustration is\nhearing that a pretty girl who was murdered left be\nhind her no photographs in pajamas or one-piece\nbathing suit.\nHave you heard about the applicant who w-as re\nfused a druggist\u2019s license by the examining board be\ncause he couldn't slice a ham thin enough?\nTIMIDITY.\nThe market it is going up\nAnd stock I\u2019d quickly grab. son.\nIf I could get a guarantee\nThere'd be no word from Babson.\nTHE OLD HOME TOWN.Stanley\nI\nI\n1\n/bobby, let me\nI BORROW YOUR.\nI SUSP, WANT TO\nISEE HOW CLOSE\n1 CAN COME TO\nTHAT FELLER\nnamthout h\\tTin\n^V. HIM-_S\n(AW <5EE,YOUJ?E\\ /s\n\\too oi-O i=ofy\ncoast/n'\nMfe WALKED'.\ns* M\n^_\n/AW LET HIT*\nI HAVE IT. EoS.\nHE WONT\n1 BREAK IT\nJS7X.N,\nIT LOOKS LIKE MARSHAL OTEY WALKER, is\nGETTING* KITTENISH. BUT KNOWING O-TEy AS\nWEL L AS WE DO, THERE S P^C3AQly\nMETHOD IN HIS MADNESS sr: tomorrows\nPAPh\u00ab FOR FURTrtcS PeTALS\n_____-. IV tW W\n*~~'ct*vTT\u00bbA,i_ Pflrn -17- la\nI\nCHAPTER 48\n\u201cThis is simply the last feather\non the camel's neck I\" declared the\nlieutenant with emphasis when the\ngirls had completed their recital of\nthe disappearance of Mme. Leclerc.\n\u201cIt\u2019s plain that Maxwell will stop\nat nothing to accomplish his ends.'\nWe know from the Madame\u2019s story\nof that affair in Paris for which\nher husband now awaits trial that\nhe. Maxwell, will do murder. So it\nbehooves us to take every precau\ntion possible. We\u2019ve been too care\nless. From now on neither Pat nor\nMargery should take the slightest\nchance. It must be, of course, that\nMadame menaced his Interests in\nsome way. Whether Bouchard and\nshe have been kidnaped and lock\ned up In some stronghold of his\nor\u2014but it hardly seems as though\nhe\u2019d go to the extreme of actual\nmurder. Still, you never can tell!\nAt ail events we must report the\nmatter to the police at once!\"\nWhereupon the big limousine\nonce more carried the party\u2014minus\nthe Madame this time\u2014down La\nfayette street to police headquarters.\nAnd to the old sergeant Rex Dallard\nreported the trick that had drawn\nMadame Leclerc into the clutches\nof Maxwell. The old policeman\nshrok his head.\n\u201clies the most dangerous type of\ncrook we have to deal with.\" he\nsaid. \u201cHe lias the brains to plot,\ntne nerve to execute and the money\nto put his schemes through. And\nhe never lets the one hand know\nwhat the other hand does! Plays a\nlone game\u2014excepting what he hires\ndone! It\u2019ll be no easy job\u2014to find\nthis young fellow and the woman.\nBut. we\u2019ll do the best we can!\"\nBut even the best, as the saying\ngoes, was \u201cnot so good.\" The old\nsergeant knew, evidently, whereof\nhe spoke. Finding Jean Bouchard\nor Madame Leclerc seemed destined\nto be a long-drawn-out job. Not a\ntrace of \"them came to the four. As\nTor old Maxwell he seemed to have\ndisappeared as effectually as Bou\nchard and the Madame.\nJimmy and his welfare! What to\ndo with Jimmy. That was the sub\nject on any and all occasions when\nthe four met. Three specialists had\nexamined him. Each one prescribed\na treatment that was different in\nseveral respects. but on one point\nthey all agreed. *immy should be\nallowed, they declared, another six\nmonths h< which to show what na\nture would do. And all prescribed\na sea voyage in tropical waters.\nIt was Marks, the lawyer, who\nprovided the su^g^tion regarding\nthe be:t merns for a sea voyage,\nbest for Jimmy and one in which\nhis frirrds mi^ht particinate.\n\"Everybody has his or her troub\nle.\" he retr.rr'-ed during the course\nrf a conversation one evening a*\nthe I yr.ne Imme. \u201cThere's an old\nfriend\u2014and client\u2014 cf mine. How\nard Wickly. lie s worth a counle\nof millions. Is in good health and\nnet yet forty. And with all that\nWho am I? In what city am I a\nJudge? For what kind of cases am I\nnoted?\nHow many women came to Vir\nginia with the first settlers in 1607?\nWhat is the symbol of Tammany\nHall?\n*\u2019Ye Judge after the flesh; I Judge\nno man.\" Where is this passage\nfound in the Bible?\nCorrectly Speaking\nWhen you are not feeling well say.\n\u25a0\u2018I am ill,\u201d not \u201cI am poorly.\"\nToday\u2019s Anniversary\nOn this clay, in 1766, Thomas Mal\nthua, the English political economist,\nwas born.\nToday's Horoscope\nPersons born on this day are very\nartistic and make large profits\nthrough this trait.\nAnswers to Fort*coin.? Questions\n1. Joseph Sabath; Chicago; di\nvorce.\n2. None.\n3. Tiger.\n4. St. John, viii, 15.\nr\u2014\nStar Lore\n\u201cA SELF-MOVER\u201d\nBy Arthur DeV. Carpenter\nWe are in receipt of a letter from\na perpetual motion, \"a self-mover\u201d;\na p.rpetval motion, a salf-mover\";\n\u2018hat ho has p; oven it, has disman\ntled the ir.ot.ument to preserve his\nsecret, tut wants to know how he\n\"tay get to demonstrate his inven\ntion before a group of Intelligent\nmen who will credit him ar.d pro\ntect his rights. The reader will say\nthese claims have the sound of a\nself-decieved man. Eleven years ago\nthe writer met a man in California\nwho had invented a perpetual mo\ntion. explained the principle and\nsaid: \u201cIn about two weeks you will\nhear all about it. as it will be writ\nten up in the papers.\u201d\n(Continued Tomorrow)\nlife for him tonight seems hardly\nworth the living.\n\"Howard was married five years\nago,\" went on Marks. \"He married\nthe girl of his boyhood dreams.\nTheir married life has been Ideal.\nA few months ago he bought a\nsplendid power yacht. Gave two\nhundred thousand dollars for it.\n\u25a0Hie craft Is two hundred feet from\nstem to gudgeon. It has fourteen\nprivate staterooms in addition to\nthe crew\u2019s quarters. It carries a\ncrew of twenty, comprising the\ncaptain, two mates, wireless oper\nators, steward, chef and second\ncook; two waiters, two cabin boys,\ntwo engineers, two oilers\u2014she burns\noil\u2014and five deck hands. The cap\ntain\u2019s and first mate's cabins are\non the top deck and adjoining the\npilot house. _ _\n\u201cMy client and his wife with a\nparty of six friends, had planned\nto leave New York this week for\na trip around the world. Last Sat\nurday she and he were out riding\nin his car. He was driving. They\nwere speeding along Madison ave\nnue wh^a he lost control for an\nInstant and smashed into a big\ntruck. His wife was hurled through\nthe windshield. She died in five\nminutes. He was unhurt\u2014physical\nly. Mentally Howard Wickly is\nclose to being a madman. Just to\nmention the yacht In his heading\nalmost drives him wild. One could\nbuy the craft mighty cheap. I\nreckon!\"\nAs the statement dropped from his\nlips Pat straightened up In her\nchair, her eyes suddenly aglow as\nthe new idea struck her.\n\"Why wouldn't that be just the\nthing for Jimmy?\" she queried as\nif she were considering the purchase\nof a new toy for him to play with.\nShe glanced around the little group\ninquiringly. \u201cA cruise of five or six\ni months through tropical waters\u2014\nthat\u2019s what tl*i doctors said!\" She\n1 turned to the lawyer. \u201cDo you sup\npose. Mr. Marks?\" she asked, \"that<\nI could buy the yacht for what he\npaid for it?\u201d\n\"I\u2019m sure you could,\" replied the\nlawyer, who knew she could buy it\nfor much less. \"And it would as you\nsay, be just the thing fcr Jimmy!\nIf you want me to I\u2019ll call him up\nin the morning and get a pnce on\nit!\u201d\nThe idea met with the instant ap\npreval of not only Rex. Prank and\nMargery, but of Aunt Lettie as well. 1\nShe always had been crazy to go I\naway on a long yachting trip, she i\ndeclared.\nMarks telephoned Pat shortly afte.\nnoon the following day, informing\nher that Wickly\u2019s yacht, the Blue- 1\nbird, could be purchased for $150,- 1\n000 cash. It was insured, he had\nteamed, for that amount with the j\npremiums paid up for six months i\nPat gave the lawyer instructions to i\nnegotiate the purchase at once with\nthe provision that she and her\nfriends should lu-st inspect it. He i\nhad already arranged for that, he\ntcld her. Pat immediately call\ned Daiiard and the doctor\nand acquainted them with the law\nyers report. As a result Margery\nand she, with Aunt Lottie and Jim\nmy met the men at their p'.tce\nnear Gramercy Park where Marks\njoined them, and the party was\ndriven to a dock near the foot of\nFifty-first street and the Hudson\nwhere the Bluebird was moored.\nCaptain Seth Lee and the first\nmate, Carl Johnson, the first engi\nneer. John Lake, the steward, Peter\nBronson and the chef, Antoine Ve\nlasse. were aboard at the time of\nthe visit. They all expressed them\nselves as pleased at the prospect of\nan early cruise. The yacht s regular t\ncrew, the captain said, was still\nwith them with the exception of j\nthree deck hands who would have to\nbe engaged.\nThe new owner-to-be and her\nfriends were escorted Over and;\nthrough the craft by Captain Lee\nand Mr. Johnson, first officer. The\nBluebird was found to be a splend\nidly built and equipped yacht. Slung\nfrom davits on the starboard side\n(DRY) LAND AT LAST?\nm\nA __\nt%, }i ?r\u00abnsfertoX'\n^S^JHE DEPT OFJUST^k\nligh up so as to permit one to walk\nmderneath along the passage be\nween cabin and rail was a late\nnodel motor boat thirty feet long\nind with a carrying capacity of\nhirty persons. On the port side\ni-ere two small boats, ordinary row\nng boats.\nThere were fourteen perfectly ap\njolnted staterooms, each with two\niouble berths, upper and lower, a\niny toilet and shower bath, three\nasy chairs and a chiffonier. These\n.taterooms were provided with\niouble-paned and screened windows\nlooking across the passageway be\ntween rail and cabin.\nThe main cabin, which also served\nis a dining cabin, was seventy feet\nlong and luxuriously furnished. Re\nmoval of the big rug permitted danc\nj ATTENTION!\ni We have added a\nRental Library to our\nt store! Come in and look\nI it over. All of the best\nsellers of all publishers. Z\nKeep abreast of the\nmost popular new books\nby renting them at\nsmalt cost!\nI HARGROVE\u2019S j;\nI Stationery Book Store j\nPhone 348\nBrownsville, Texas\na\u2014\u25a04444W\nWeed less\nPain?\nSome folks take pain for granted.\nThey let a cold \"run its course.'!\nThey wait for their headaches to \u201cwear off.T\nIf suffering from neuralgia or from neuritis,\nthey rely on feeling better in the morning.\nMeantime, they suffer unnecessary pain.\nUnnecessary, because there is an antidote.\nBayer Aspirin always offers immediate relief\nfrom various aches and pains we once had to\nendure. If pain persists, consult your doctor\nas to its cause.\nSave yourself a lot of pain and discomfort\nthrough the many uses of Bayer Aspirin. Pro\ntect yourself by buying the genuine. Bayer is\naafe. Always the same. All drugstores.\n.BAYER ASPIRIN\ntAapina is the trade mark of Bayer Manufacture of Monoaeeticaeideeter of SaUcylicaeid\nlng on ft floor built like the runway\nof ft bowling alley. The engine room\nwas. of course, below decks, the up\nper part Inclosed with a four-foot\npassageway on each side. Forward\nof the galley was the crew's quar\nters. Taken in its entirety the yacht\nwas the ideal pleasure craft for a\nparty of ten to twenty persons on a\nround-the-world voyage.\nPat's party, it was noted, would\nnumber nine, namely: Margery,\nAunt Lottie, Lucy Pine and herself 1\nwith Jimmy, Rex Dallard, Dr. Gor\ndon and the lawyer, Marks, and his\nwife. The girls and Aunt Lottie\nhad alreadv met Mrs Marks on\ntwo or three occasions.\n<TO BE CONTINUED)\nEat At\nAnthony\u2019s Waffle\nShop\n517 12 St Phone 983\nA. TAMM\nBlue Printing and\nSupplies\nHarlingen, Texas\n[^PROSPERITY\nProsperity for Brownsville and\nthe Valley is a tangible, able-to\nbe-seen condition. Citrus grove.*\nare beginning to bloom vege\ntables are commanding good\nprices generally the interna\ntional airport and the bright\nprospects for a deep water port\u2014\nall are encouraging a splendid\nbusiness outlook for Brownsville\nand the Valley.\nLet us. as your bank, help\nyou with any problems you\nmay wish to discuss with us.\nFirst National Bank\nEstablished in 1891\nBROWNSVILLE, TEXAS\n1\nj TITLE INSURANCE\nWhen you borrow money on real estate, many loan companies re- I\nquire the title to be insured. Ihe best test of whether a title ui\ninsurable, is to have it insured. Require a title insurance policy\nwhen yon buy.\nVALLEY ABSTRACT COMPANY\nPrompt Title Service\nr<\nwwnsTuie\nOpposite Court Bouse\nPhone 1184\nE. Harriman Bird.\nPhone 93","height":"36420","width":"27312"}}
